s trees one after another"},{"type":"text","text":" (sequential), unlike random forests' parallel approach"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Each tree learns from errors"},{"type":"text","text":": Focuses on what model got wrong earlier"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Minimizes loss function"},{"type":"text","text":": Uses gradient to find direction that reduces prediction error"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Shrinkage (learning rate)"},{"type":"text","text":": Controls learning speed to prevent overfitting"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"More accurate than random forests"},{"type":"text","text":": When tuned properly, often best on tabular data"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Prone to overfitting"},{"type":"text","text":": Needs careful parameter tuning"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Sensitive to outliers"},{"type":"text","text":": Poor performance on noisy data"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Slower fitting, faster prediction"},{"type":"text","text":": Long training time, short inference time"}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Popular libraries"},{"type":"text","text":": XGBoost, LightGBM, CatBoost dominate competitions"}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Gradient boosting is the \"step-by-step improvement\" approach to machine learning — by iteratively training trees to fix previous mistakes and combining them with careful scaling, it achieves higher accuracy than random forests, but requires careful tuning to avoid overfitting on noisy data."}]}]}}
